comment: Liverpool City Councillors a few years ago where going to remove Penny Lane from the history books because of links to a slave trader named John Penny, however a young 7 year old lad attending a local primary school informed them that in fact it was actually down to persons having to pay a penny to cross a nearby bridge, he also informed them of the devastating effect this would have on the local community and the City as a whole losing millions of pounds in lost revenue.

The Bassline during verse (is inspired from Bach's Goldberg Variations, esp. variation 4 and 5 where the theme is clearly stated-- Goldberg Variations were made popular by Glenn Gould's 1955 recording. It took the world by storm as bach had been considered so difficult to play (Gould played much of it at a breakneck speed--most played bach far to slow due to the virtuosity his work demands). Thus bach had been relegated to academia, and private recitals rather than the public performance let alone recordings. Glenn changed that perception. Thanks Beatles for using the beauty of bach and making it palatable for the masses!

DESTROY THE BEATLES
I readily admit it, my brothers.  I have tried to destroy The Beatles.  Yes, my brothers, for decades I have tried to destroy them.  Sleepless nights.  Months spent reading through the world's great libraries. Thousands of plans drawn up on blueprint paper.  I have consulted with the finest minds in the universe, finally assembling a small team from the most brilliant among them.  For seven years we lived in a bunker constructed under the Atlantic Ocean, focused on one goal: DESTROY THE BEATLES.  Meetings.  Deadlines.  Screaming matches.  Threats of having them ejected into the dark and dour ocean.  But now I admit defeat, my brothers.  It cannot be done.  The Beatles cannot be destroyed.  They are eternal, and their music shall cover the Earth like an eternal blanket of beauty. comment: Was on Penny Lane recently. Barbershop is still there. Also the church where Paul and his brother sang in the choir. The church has a graveyard that includes the final resting place of one "Eleanor Rigby," who was interned there in 1939 (age 44). McCartney undoubtedly passed the tombstone many times on his way to choir practice, but has no memory of having ever seen it. There's no "roundabout" on Penny Lane any more. It's a traffic island now.

comment: The trumpet player who did the incredible piccolo trumpet part passed away not too long ago. I remember many years ago reading that it was a sped up trumpet, it was not! He took offense to that false information and made sure to dispel it whenever he could. Paul McCartney saw classical trumpeter, David Mason, on TV from Guildford Cathedral playing Bach's Brandenburg Concerto #2, which features a piccolo trumpet in the extreme high range. That's when he decided to use it and the man was hired.
